### Purpose of OOAD

Identifying the object of the system and their relationships and then making a design that will be converted into executables using OO languages.

### UML

Unified Modeling Language.

Not a programming language.

Used for both non-software and software systems.

The pictorial representation used to make software blueprints

It helps us in:

Visualizing

Specifying

Constructing

and Documenting the software system.

### Relationship b/w OOAD and UML

Has direct relation with OOAD.

If we look at a class diagram, interactional diagram, object diagram, or more they are all basically designed based on objects.

### UML Building Blocks

First, we make a conceptual model then we build the system.

**How to master conceptual model?**

By learning the following three major elements:

1. UML building blocks
  
2. Rules to connect the building blocks
  
3. Common mechanism of UML
  

### UML BB

```mermaid
flowchart
BB(Building Blocks) ---> T(Things)
BB ---> R(Relationships)
BB ---> D(Diagrams)
```

### Things in UML

Things are the most important building blocks of UML. Things include:

```mermaid
graph TB
 uml[Things]
 structural[Structural Things]
 behavioral[Behavioural Things]
 grouping[Grouping Things]
 annotational[Annotational Things] 
uml --> structural
 uml --> behavioral
 uml --> grouping
 uml --> annotational
```

#### Structural Things

Structural thing defines the static part of the model. They represent the physical and conceptual elements.

```mermaid
flowchart
classDef yellow fill:#FEF445, stroke:#652CB3, stroke-width:2px, color:black
ST(Structural Things):::yellow ----o C(Class)
ST ----o O(Interface)
ST ----o Col(Collaboration)
ST ----o U(Usecase)
ST ----o Com(Component)
ST ----o N(Node)
```

**Class:** is a set of objects having similar responsibilities, characteristics and behaviours.

```mermaid
classDiagram
class Duck{
+String beakColor
+swim()
+quack()
}
```

**Interface:** Define the set operations which specify the responsibility of the class.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Collaboration:** Define an interaction between elements

**Use Case:** Define a set of actions performed by the system to achieve a specific goal.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Component:** Describe the physical part of the system

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Node:** It's the physical element of the system that exists at run time.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Behavioural Things

Behavioural things represent the dynamic part of the UML model. Behavioural things include:

**Interactions:** Defined as behaviour that consists of a set of messages exchanged among the objects to achieve a specific goal.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant A as Asif
    participant J as Asim
    A->>J: Hello Asim, how are you?
    J->>A: Great!
```

**State Machine:** is a sequence of states an object goes through in response to an event. An event is a factor that causes a change in state.

```mermaid
    stateDiagram-v2
        State1: Loged Out State
        note right of State1
           Event: User Clicks Login Button
        end note
    [*]--> State1
        State1 --> Logged_in
        note left of  Logged_in: Dashboard Page Accessed
        Logged_in-->[*]
```

### Grouping Things

It's a mechanism that is used to group the elements of the UML model. They include:

**Package:** Package is the only grouping thing available for gathering structural and behavioural things.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Annotation Things

It's a mechanism that is used to capture comments, remarks and descriptions.

**Note:** is the only thing available for displaying or rendering comments and constraints of the UML elements.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Relationships

### Association

The association is a set of links that connects the elements of the UML model.
